## 6. Parametric Model 1: Multiple Linear Regression

Multiple linear regression is used as the first interpretable modeling approach. It assumes a mostly linear relationship between predictors and final grade. This makes it useful as a starting point and as a good-enough-fast model when interpretability matters.

```{r train-mlr}
set.seed(5300)

mlr_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "lm",
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected
)

mlr_model
```

## 7. Parametric Model 2: LASSO Regression

LASSO regression adds regularization to the linear model. It can shrink less useful predictors toward zero, which helps with feature selection and overfitting control.

```{r train-lasso}
set.seed(5300)

lasso_grid <- expand.grid(
  alpha = 1,
  lambda = 10^seq(-4, 1, length = 20)
)

lasso_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "glmnet",
  preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
  tuneGrid = lasso_grid,
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected
)

lasso_model
```

## 8. Flexible Regression Model: Generalized Additive Model

The GAM is included because the EDA plots showed that some relationships may not be strictly linear. A GAM can model smoother nonlinear patterns while remaining more interpretable than some black-box machine learning models.

```{r train-gam}
set.seed(5300)

gam_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "gamSpline",
  preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected
)

gam_model
```

## 9. Tree-Based Ensemble Model: Random Forest

Random forest is used because it can capture nonlinear patterns and interactions without requiring the same linearity assumptions as multiple linear regression. It is often a strong candidate when predictor relationships are complex.

```{r train-random-forest}
set.seed(5300)

rf_grid <- expand.grid(
  mtry = c(4, 8, 12),
  splitrule = "variance",
  min.node.size = c(5, 10)
)

rf_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "ranger",
  tuneGrid = rf_grid,
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected,
  importance = "permutation",
  num.trees = 300
)

rf_model
```

## 10. Tree-Based Ensemble Model: Gradient Boosted Trees

Gradient boosted trees are included because they build many small trees sequentially, with each tree learning from the errors of the prior trees. This can produce strong predictive performance, but it may also increase the risk of overfitting if tuning is not handled carefully.

```{r train-gbm}
set.seed(5300)

gbm_grid <- expand.grid(
  interaction.depth = c(1, 3),
  n.trees = c(100, 200),
  shrinkage = c(0.05, 0.10),
  n.minobsinnode = c(10)
)

gbm_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "gbm",
  tuneGrid = gbm_grid,
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected,
  verbose = FALSE
)

gbm_model
```

## 11. Support Vector Machine

The support vector machine model uses a radial basis function kernel. The radial kernel is a practical choice when EDA suggests that relationships may be nonlinear and when the model needs flexibility beyond a straight-line decision surface.

```{r train-svm}
set.seed(5300)

svm_grid <- expand.grid(
  sigma = c(0.005, 0.01, 0.02),
  C = c(0.5, 1, 2)
)

svm_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "svmRadial",
  preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
  tuneGrid = svm_grid,
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected
)

svm_model
```

## 12. Single-Hidden-Layer Neural Network

The final technical report required a deep learning-style model with one hidden layer. In this portfolio version, I use a lightweight single-hidden-layer neural network to keep the report reproducible in a standard R environment.

The required architecture is documented as:

- Input nodes: number of encoded predictors
- Hidden layer nodes: 2 × number of input nodes
- Hidden activation: ReLU in the technical specification
- Output: numeric final grade prediction

Because the standard R `nnet` package does not use ReLU activation in the same way as modern deep learning frameworks, this page uses `nnet` as a reproducible approximation and documents the architecture decision. A production version could implement the exact ReLU architecture with Keras or Torch.

```{r train-neural-network}
set.seed(5300)

encoded_predictor_count <- ncol(train_encoded)
hidden_nodes <- min(2 * encoded_predictor_count, 25)

nnet_grid <- expand.grid(
  size = c(5, 10, hidden_nodes),
  decay = c(0.001, 0.01)
)

nnet_model <- train(
  model_formula,
  data = train_df,
  method = "nnet",
  preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
  tuneGrid = nnet_grid,
  trControl = cv_control,
  metric = metric_selected,
  linout = TRUE,
  trace = FALSE,
  maxit = 500
)

nnet_model
```

